class TreeNode {
    constructor(val) {
        this.val = val;
        this.left = this.right = null;
    }
}

function delNodes(root, to_delete) {
    const to_delete_set = new Set(to_delete);
    const remaining_trees = [];

    function removeNodes(node) {
        if (node === null) return null;
        node.left = removeNodes(node.left);
        node.right = removeNodes(node.right);
        if (to_delete_set.has(node.val)) {
            if (node.left) remaining_trees.push(node.left);
            if (node.right) remaining_trees.push(node.right);
            return null;
        }
        return node;
    }

    if (removeNodes(root)) remaining_trees.push(root);
    return remaining_trees;
}
```


    The algorithm uses recursion to solve the problem. The algorithm can be divided into the following steps:

1. Create a helper method named `removeNodes`, which takes a tree node as a parameter and returns the node itself (a tree) after deleting nodes in to_delete list.
- Use a set for `to_delete` values for efficient lookups.
2. Use a recursive strategy for the helper method:
   - If it reaches a null node, simply return null.
   - Recursively call the method for the left and right children of the node.
   - If the node's value is in the `to_delete_set`:
       - Add the left child to the `remaining_trees` list if it is not null.
       - Add the right child to the `remaining_trees` list if it is not null.
       - Return null.
   - Otherwise, return the node itself.
3. Call the helper method for the root node and add it to the remaining_trees list if it is not null.
4. Return the list of remaining_trees.

Overall, the algorithm's time complexity is O(n) where n is the number of nodes in the tree. This is because it traverses each node in the tree once.

